# arvo-hash — Design

L2 hash-domain types and algorithm contracts. Ships a domain alias
over the arvo-bits opaque-bit container, generic trait contracts
for hash algorithms, and `Fnv1a<const N: BitWidth>` as the first
concrete `Hasher` implementation, with both runtime trait form and
const-fn `hash_const` entry usable in compile-time positions.

`#![no_std]`, no alloc. Depends on arvo-bits only.

## Why this crate exists

Hashes (content hashes, name hashes, pass-key identity) are numeric
algorithms on opaque bit-patterns. The stack needed one home for
the runtime carriers. arvo-bits provides the generic Bits container;
arvo-hash provides the domain vocabulary (ContentHash) and the algo
contracts (Hasher, HasherExt) consumers parameterise over.

Crate size is deliberately thin today. Growth surface (concrete
algorithms, cryptographic hashes as a sibling crate, semantic
aliases beyond ContentHash) is tracked in BACKLOG.

## Types

### ContentHash

A type alias for arvo-bits `Bits<{ width_of(28) }, Hot>`. Matches
hilavitkutin-str's low-28-bit FNV content-hash identity, produced by
`Fnv1a::<{ width_of(28) }>::hash_const`. Consumers that want a named
type at call sites (hilavitkutin-persistence StringTableEntry,
vehje resolver pass-key identity) bind ContentHash instead of the
raw `Bits<{ width_of(28) }, Hot>`.

```rust
pub type ContentHash = arvo_bits::Bits<{ arvo::width_of(28) }, arvo::Hot>;
```

A direct type alias rather than a newtype: the semantic domain is
fully captured by the bit width; no additional invariants warrant
a distinct type.

## Algorithm contracts

### Hasher (canonical, streaming)

```rust
pub trait Hasher<const N: arvo::BitWidth> {
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]);
    fn finalize(self) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N>;
}
```

Streaming hash: feed bytes incrementally, finalise to an N-bit
opaque pattern. Consumers implementing a hash algorithm implement
this trait.

The `BitWidth` const-generic param type is from arvo L0 (a `Uint7`
ConstParamTy newtype). Bare `u8` is no longer in the public surface;
the `arvo::width_of(n)` const-fn helper provides call-site ergonomics
in turbofish.

### HasherExt (oneshot convenience, blanket impl)

```rust
pub trait HasherExt<const N: arvo::BitWidth>: Hasher<N> + Sized {
    /// One-shot: update with the complete input, then finalize.
    fn hash(mut self, bytes: &[u8]) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N> {
        self.update(bytes);
        self.finalize()
    }
}
impl<H: Hasher<N>, const N: arvo::BitWidth> HasherExt<N> for H {}
```

HasherExt's default method provides oneshot ergonomics over any
Hasher implementor. The blanket impl means every Hasher automatically
exposes a .hash(bytes) one-shot form; implementors do not write
their own oneshot path. Mirrors the round-202604201048 Encoder /
Decoder + EncoderExt / DecoderExt pattern: streaming is canonical,
oneshot is a derived convenience.

## Concrete algorithm: Fnv1a<N>

`Fnv1a<const N: BitWidth>` is the first concrete `Hasher` impl
shipped by arvo-hash. Implements canonical FNV-1a-64 (offset basis
`0xcbf29ce484222325`, prime `0x100000001b3`). For N less than 64,
the low-N bits of the 64-bit accumulator are returned. Matches
`hilavitkutin-str::const_fnv1a` semantics for the 28-bit content-hash
case (which `ContentHash` aliases).

```rust
pub struct Fnv1a<const N: arvo::BitWidth>
where Hot: UContainerFor<N>;

impl<const N: arvo::BitWidth> Hasher<N> for Fnv1a<N>
where Hot: UContainerFor<N>
{
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]) { /* runtime FNV-1a-64, mask to N bits */ }
    fn finalize(self) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N> { /* return masked accumulator */ }
}

impl<const N: arvo::BitWidth> Fnv1a<N>
where Hot: UContainerFor<N>
{
    /// Compile-time entry point: hash a byte slice, mask to N bits.
    pub const fn hash_const(bytes: &[u8]) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N> {
        /* const-fn FNV-1a-64 + mask */
    }
}
```

The runtime trait impl and the const-fn entry point coexist; both
compute the same algorithm. The const-fn variant is what compile-time
validation downstream consumes (e.g. the hilavitkutin app-builder
formalisation round, which gates `.build()` on per-store hash-set
membership proven via `Fnv1a::<{ width_of(64) }>::hash_const`
applied to `core::any::type_name::<T>()`).

| Item | Form |
|---|---|
| Type | `pub struct Fnv1a<const N: arvo::BitWidth>` where `Hot: UContainerFor<N>` |
| Runtime impl | `impl<const N: arvo::BitWidth> Hasher<N> for Fnv1a<N>` |
| Const-fn entry | `pub const fn hash_const(bytes: &[u8]) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N>` |
| ContentHash producer | `Fnv1a::<{ arvo::width_of(28) }>::hash_const(s.as_bytes())` |

The `bytes: &[u8]` parameter shape matches what const-fn callers can
produce (e.g. `core::any::type_name::<T>().as_bytes()`). Wrapping in
a higher-level boundary stays out of scope for this round.

## Usage

Downstream code parameterises over the trait; swapping algorithm
is a type-parameter change, not a call-site rewrite.

Streaming:

```rust
fn intern_chunks<H: Hasher<28>>(mut hasher: H, chunks: &[&[u8]]) -> ContentHash {
    for chunk in chunks { hasher.update(chunk); }
    hasher.finalize()
}
```

One-shot:

```rust
fn intern<H: HasherExt<28>>(hasher: H, bytes: &[u8]) -> ContentHash {
    hasher.hash(bytes)
}
```

To swap algorithm, change the type the caller supplies. No site
edits; the trait signatures stay put.

## Dependencies

- arvo-bits (L1): provides Bits<const N: u8> (the underlying
  container) plus BitWidth / BitAccess trait bounds.

arvo-hash does not depend on arvo L0 directly. Future algorithm
modules may bring in arvo deps as needed; ship-time scope keeps
the dep surface minimal.

## What this crate does NOT contain

- Other concrete hash algorithms (xxHash, CRC32); follow-up rounds. Fnv1a ships in this crate.
- Cryptographic hashes (SHA, BLAKE); out of scope entirely.
  A sibling arvo-crypto crate covers cryptographic needs if they
  surface.
- Semantic aliases beyond ContentHash; consumers that need
  NameHash, KeyHash, or similar start with their own local alias
  over ContentHash or Bits<N> and promote to arvo-hash once
  patterns stabilise.
- rkyv Archive impls; consumers define Archive at their boundary.
- Owned byte buffers; all hashing takes &[u8] input.

## Design rule

`#![no_std]`, no alloc. Algorithm-agnostic: the crate defines the
contract, not the implementation. Consumer code parameterises over
the trait; concrete algorithms ship as implementors in follow-up
rounds.

